<paragraph id="E34236D4BC4FFFDD51B9BDFEFD08FAEF" blockId="9.[151,1437,909,1404]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">
Comments: The hairs on the mesoscutum and mesoscutellum of the 
<typeStatus id="3C468876BC4FFFDD52ADBDFEFB87FA9B" box="[979,1082,1269,1295]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">lectotype</typeStatus>
have blackish rachis and whitish branches, as well as some yellow hairs on the tegula, anterior area of the mesoscutum and on the pronotal lobe. According to the original description, both females belonged to Dejean’s collection. This species has been only recorded in South America (
<bibRefCitation id="876C4B25BC4FFFDD50ADBC6AFD14FAEF" author="Moure, J. S. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. &amp; Vivallo, F." box="[467,681,1377,1404]" pageId="9" pageNumber="32" pagination="83 - 142" refId="ref10644" refString="Moure, J. S., Melo, G. A. R. &amp; Vivallo, F. (2007) Centridini Cockerell &amp; Cockerell. In: Moure, J. S., Urban, D. &amp; Melo, G. A. R. (Orgs.), Catalogue of Bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) in the Neotropical Region. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitiba, pp. 83 - 142." type="book chapter" year="2007">
Moure 
<emphasis id="D189EAC6BC4FFFDD5358BC69FDEAFAEF" box="[550,599,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="32">et al</emphasis>
., 2007
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
